# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1777-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The **1777 Maryland gubernatorial election** was held on February 13, 1777, in order to elect the First Governor of Maryland.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1777-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Candidate Thomas Johnson was elected by the Maryland General Assembly against Samuel Chase and other candidates.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1777-maryland-gubernatorial-election] On election day, February 13, 1777, Thomas Johnson was elected by the Maryland General Assembly.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1777-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Johnson was sworn in as the 1st Governor of Maryland on March 21, 1777.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1778-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The **1778 Maryland gubernatorial election** was held on November 9, 1778, in order to elect the Governor of Maryland.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1778-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Governor Thomas Johnson was easily re-elected by the Maryland General Assembly as he ran unopposed.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1778-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The exact results of this election are unknown.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1778-maryland-gubernatorial-election] On election day, November 9, 1778, Thomas Johnson was re-elected by the Maryland General Assembly.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1778-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Johnson was sworn in for his second term on November 10, 1778.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1779-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The **1779 Maryland gubernatorial election** was held on November 8, 1779, in order to elect the Governor of Maryland.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1779-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Candidate Thomas Sim Lee was elected by the Maryland General Assembly against his opponent Edward Lloyd.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1779-maryland-gubernatorial-election] On election day, November 8, 1779, Thomas Sim Lee was elected by the Maryland General Assembly.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1779-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Lee was sworn in as the 2nd Governor of Maryland on November 12, 1779.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1780-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The **1780 Maryland gubernatorial election** was held on November 13, 1780, in order to elect the Governor of Maryland.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1780-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Governor Thomas Sim Lee was easily re-elected by the Maryland General Assembly as he ran unopposed.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1780-maryland-gubernatorial-election] On election day, November 13, 1780, Thomas Sim Lee was re-elected by the Maryland General Assembly.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1780-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Lee was sworn in for his second term on November 15, 1780.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1781-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The **1781 Maryland gubernatorial election** was held on November 19, 1781, in order to elect the Governor of Maryland.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1781-maryland-gubernatorial-election] On election day, November 19, 1781, Thomas Sim Lee was re-elected by the Maryland General Assembly.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1781-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Lee was sworn in for his third term on November 20, 1781.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1782-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The **1782 Maryland gubernatorial election** was held on November 15, 1782, in order to elect the Governor of Maryland.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1782-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Candidate William Paca was elected by the Maryland General Assembly against his opponent, former President of the Maryland Senate Daniel of St.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1782-maryland-gubernatorial-election] On election day, November 15, 1782, William Paca was elected by the Maryland General Assembly.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1782-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Paca was sworn in as the 3rd Governor of Maryland on November 16, 1782.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1783-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The **1783 Maryland gubernatorial election** was held on November 22, 1783, in order to elect the Governor of Maryland.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1783-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Governor William Paca was easily re-elected by the Maryland General Assembly as he ran unopposed.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1783-maryland-gubernatorial-election] On election day, November 22, 1783, William Paca was re-elected by the Maryland General Assembly.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1783-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Paca was sworn in for his second term on November 22, 1783.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The **1864 Maryland gubernatorial election** took place on November 8, 1864.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Union Party Governor Augustus Bradford did not run for re-election.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Union Party candidate Thomas Swann defeated Democratic candidate Ezekiel F.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The Union Party was a Southern Unionist political movement which supported the Lincoln administration.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Most Unionists were former Whigs who had joined the Know Nothing movement in the 1850s, while a minority were Radical Republicans or War Democrats.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election] The party supported the re-election of Abraham Lincoln under the banner of the National Union Party.
[src:1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election/1864-maryland-gubernatorial-election] Swann took his oath of office on January 11, 1865, but by a provision of the 1864 State Constitution, he did not actually become Governor until January 10, 1866.
